00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:06.740
And lastly, one of the things
that was new in Android 4.3 is

00:33:06.740 --> 00:33:09.020
this new optical
bounds feature.

00:33:09.020 --> 00:33:13.920
So basically, if before your
nine-patches had extra spacing

00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:16.270
around there to account for
things like drop shadows and

00:33:16.270 --> 00:33:19.370
glows and such, and that caused
your UI elements to not

00:33:19.370 --> 00:33:20.525
really visually line up.

00:33:20.525 --> 00:33:24.670
And Kirill Grouchnikov did a
fabulous blog post about this

00:33:24.670 --> 00:33:26.050
specific problem and
how they address in

00:33:26.050 --> 00:33:27.540
this Google Play Store.

00:33:27.540 --> 00:33:30.140
But if you are having this
problem, and you want to

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:34.900
address it, as of Android 4.3,
there's a new feature called

00:33:34.900 --> 00:33:36.940
optical bounds in
nine-patches.

00:33:36.940 --> 00:33:39.900
So basically in your
nine-patches, you have these

00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:43.600
extra red markings to indicate
that this should be the

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:46.340
negative margins that you should
shift the UI elements

00:33:46.340 --> 00:33:51.720
to, so that the left visual edge
or the left optical edge

00:33:51.720 --> 00:33:56.050
aligns with other items along
that line, along that edge.

00:33:56.050 --> 00:33:58.940
So it's new in Android 4.3.

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:02.580
You go from a sloppy layout here
on the left, to something

00:34:02.580 --> 00:34:04.960
a little more clean and
well-aligned on the right.

